			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Since it is obvious that a rebuttal of the propaganda promulgated by the 'public' school system is needed, I am starting a new thread concerning the rights vs. priviledge issue, in general, as opposed to Poppa's driving thread.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Correct, but rights are granted by government/society in the first place.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Wrong.  There was a HUGE change in this circa 1776, in case they didn't tell you about it.  Prior to the Declaration of Independence the King, by whatever title he was known, owned everything, including YOU.  Only he had rights, everyone else had whatever priviledges he decided to pass out.  The PEOPLE of this country took arms, and through lucky circumstance, tossed his %@$# out of government and took SOVEREINTY unto themselves.  You can @#%$ and moan about the fact they attributed their inherant rights as God given, but they took them in hand, by force of arms, the traditional method of acquiring power and property.  (Rights derive from property, btw.)  After various other arraingments they instituted the Constitution, which grats TO government SOME priviledges, and they continued to reserve all rights unto themselves.  Rights derive from God, or from yourself, if you prefer not to involve the Almighty.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I understand the difference between rights and privileges fairly clearly, but the fact of human society is that those in power determine whether something is a right or a privilege. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately true, but that doesn't make it right, nor does that mean it conforms to the actual Constitution.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Even a revolution doesn't change that, as the rights/privileges are still being determined by those in power (in that case, the revolutionaries). </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Like I said above, they took it, they passed it on to us.  It's up to us to keep it.  Personally, I agree with them, my rights are inherant, and God given.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It's entirely concerned with making sure that federal government cannot overrun the sovereignty of a given State, not with individual personal rights. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If that's what you think, you are reading it wrong.  In fact, you are reading the whole Bill of Rights wrong.  The first 10 were instituted, and in fact, insisted on, in order to preserve INDIVIDUAL rights.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I may be wrong, but it seems that you're trying to argue that if the Constitution/Bill of Rights does not specifically state that you do not have the right to something, then you have that right. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Hmm, that's one reading.  The Constitution gives a limited list of what the Federal government is allowed to do.  Everything else belongs to individuals, or States.  If not explicitly allocated to the States, it belongs to the individuals.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">As far as the 2nd Amendment goes, I think you have them confused. That Amendment is commonly known as the right to bear arms, although that's more what it has turned into as opposed to what it was intended to be. The 2nd Amendment was created to allow the right of a State to maintain an organized militia and to prevent the federal government from disarming the members of that militia and thereby leaving those people helpless against governmental abuse. It has since turned into something else entirely, mainly as a result of groups like the NRA. I don't necessarily think this is a bad thing, although there are a lot of pros to strict gun control provided it was effectively enforced (which it wouldn't be in the current state of this country). The original purpose of the Amendment is null and void, as no militia in this country has the training and armament necessary to defend itself from the government. Personal firearms and light combat training &lt; tanks and trained soldiers with modern military equipment. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
What a load of hogwash.
<br />

<br />
That's the anti-gunner lie, based on a misreading of a secondary clause.  The Second Amendment, like all of the first 10, elucidates SOME of the rights of the PEOPLE, i.e. individuals.  The Right to Bear Arms is an individual right, and intended to document and specifiy the inherant right of individuals to own MILITARY grade hardware.  In fact, the ONLY Supreme Court decision directly concerning the 2nd held that some fella didn't have a right to a particular shotgun specifically because it DIDN'T have military virtue, which is a bogus decision anyway, as shotguns have particular utility as a military weapon, just ask past and present members of the military.  This is exactly the kind of misinformation now taught in the public schools, no wonder you are so wrong.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Before someone speaks up on that effectiveness point: yes, it's possible to temporarily disable a tank with common household items. I forget who it was that brought that up last time. Your chances of doing it, however, with soldiers guarding the tank, much less with someone inside it, are very small. See what happened in Iraq for details. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Immaterial.  It means nothing.  Chance of success is not guaranteed.  The accutraments to attempt it are.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Excuse me, but if you aren't alive, you can't exercise your property rights. Life comes before property. No life, then no property. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Immaterial.  Your estate would own your body after your death, as it owns your other property until it is dealt with.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">And if you own your own body, you should be able to sell it into slavery (oh boy!). After all, if you can't sell it, you don't own it. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
At one time you did.  Ever hear of indentured servitude?  You can still enter into long term contracts that amount to the same thing.  So, an invalid argument.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Due process? Like voter registration due process? Oh, so you really have to ask permission to not be killed. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
HUH?  Did you read what I wrote?  Do you understand the term due process?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">This whole right/privilege routine is about as useful as arguing over which came first, the chicken or the egg...or who would win a fight between cavemen and astronauts...or how many angels can dance on the head of a pin. The only people who really seem concerned about it these days are political cultists. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
If you don't know your rights, it is MUCH easier to take them from you.  You can even be talked into thinking they are priviledges granted by the government.  You flunk the Constitution.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Scientologists seek only evolution to higher states of being for the individual and for Society. A civilization without insanity, without criminals, and without war, where the able can prosper and honest beings can have rights, and where Man is free to rise to greater heights, are the aims of Scientology. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yeah, right.  You really believe that.  I met L. Ron Scamster.  I knew people who were in the bar (at a WorldCon I think) when he made his drunken boast.  It's a scam, using the cult model, to tap people for money.  It seems to be especially successful on rich and famous people who have no moral foundation, and who probably feel guilty about their success.
<br />

<br />
Whatever you may think of Bednarik's lecture style, if you really want to know what the Constitution is all about, you should put in the time to check out his lectures.  As he, and others, point out, we don't have to wonder what the writers of the Constitution meant, because they wrote down what the meant.  Check out the Federalist Papers, and the Anti-Federalist Papers.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
