				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Wrong. There was a HUGE change in this circa 1776, in case they didn't tell you about it. Prior to the Declaration of Independence the King, by whatever title he was known, owned everything, including YOU. Only he had rights, everyone else had whatever priviledges he decided to pass out. The PEOPLE of this country took arms, and through lucky circumstance, tossed his %@$# out of government and took SOVEREINTY unto themselves.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
That in no way conflicts with what I said, which was "rights are granted by government/society in the first place."  Monarchy is still a government, and people leading a revolt and changing what their rights are still a form of government or a function of society.
<br />

<br />
I went through two years of law school before I decided I disliked the concept of being a lawyer.  I spent almost a full year of that studying Constitutional law.  I don't know where you got the idea that the first ten Amendments were concerned wholly with individual peoples' rights.  The first and tenth deal with the rights of groups and the individual states.
<br />

<br />
The 2nd is NOT the right to own military grade hardware, Fallonn.  I don't know where the hell <span style="font-style: italic">that</span> idea came from.  The 2nd Amendment was the right of the state to maintain an organized militia, and to keep people from being disarmed and therefore defenseless against tyranny or abuse by the government.  That is it, end of list.  I was not saying that I see anything wrong with owning guns, and in fact I personally see nothing wrong with owning guns.  That does not, however, negate the fact that the original intent of the amendment has gotten warped over the years, as have many of the others.
<br />

<br />
Why the hell did you feel a need to start a whole new thread on this when there's several already going?  You state it as an attempt to counter "propoganda promulgated by the public school system", but you're making a massive assumption right there that views people express on the matter are parroted from what they were taught (in most of our cases) 10+ years ago, and making the assumption in the first place that that is what they were taught.
<br />

<br />
Flarestar Bladesinger<br />
