			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				I would like to point out that in the entire history of the constitution, there is NOTHING in it (with one exception) that limits the individual. Everything in the constitution outlines the limits of government.
<br />

<br />
The only exception to this rule was prohibition, and it was struck out a few years after it's disasterous adoption. The framework of our federal government is specificly a limited one. It is that way by design and those limits only get spelled out for government.
<br />

<br />
The Bill of Rights was adopted several years later specificly spelling out more limits on government. Notice that the constitution doesn't say that the people get to have this right or that right. The constitution is always phrased to specify limits on government.
<br />

<br />
The preamble to the Bill of Rights starts with:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
THE Conventions of a number of the States, having at the time of their adopting the Constitution, expressed a desire, in order to prevent misconstruction or abuse of its powers, that further declaratory and restrictive clauses should be added: And as extending the ground of public confidence in the Government, will best ensure the beneficent ends of its institution."
<br />
<a href="http://www.archives.gov/national_archives_experience/charters/bill_of_rights_transcript.html" target="_blank">http://www.archives.gov/national_archives_experience/charters/bill_of_rights_transcript.html</a>
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
"In order to prevent misconstruction or abuse of its powers"
<br />

<br />
The constitution is written only to delineate the limits of government and to forbid it limiting it's people especially in certain areas like religion, free speach, property, due process, etc.
<br />

<br />
Rights are natural and not given by government. Government exists through the willfull granting of privelege to government by the people in order to have a harmonious community. 
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
The monarchy dropped it's ownership of us and it's subjugation of our natural rights were realized when the Paris Treaty 1783 was signed.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
